<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="45" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="2.[2022,2616,1355,1781]" lastBlockId="2.[1410,2619,1788,3320]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2022,2178,1355,1388]" pageId="2" pageNumber="45">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[2193,2411,1355,1388]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" species="kappleri">Dasypus kappler</taxonomicName>
: Krauss, 1862, 
<materialsCitation pageId="2" pageNumber="45">“den Urwaldern des Marowiniflusses in Surinam”</materialsCitation>
(= primeval forests near the Marowijne River, Suriname). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krauss" authorityYear="1862" box="[2022,2244,1512,1545]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="2" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kappleri">Dasypus kappleri</taxonomicName>
has been considered dis- tinct enough to warrant separation in its own subgenus, Hyperoambon; some have argued that this name should be elevated to a genus, but this has not been widely adopted. Others have proposed that the subspecies are distinct enough to be recognized as separate species, but this also has not been generally accepted. Three subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
